<text>It was a great campsite. It is more desert than forest at the camp but there are a few trees at various campsites. We had 14 people stay at tent group site 6. We brought 2 camp stoves and a stand up bbq. It is going to be windy so prepare to have some dirt in your tents. You'll need plenty of stakes for your tents. There is no fire wood so bring your own. We went through 9 bundles in two nights. Kern river is super close for fishing and swimming. There are single use restrooms and structural restrooms around the campsite. There is also various water spouts around camp. But you should also bring water and TP.<//text><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPG3JRrP7g5ZacgPjDIuOzVWiFqJ13kpyYL3SPr=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNbzNhaYOqn_kjDPdCFYGzyrpQyrt9n-IEzVIT7=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP045DMF5azXlQzDz2RE_EYm30P5GqcfWVT2I4t=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOSRQ1JWNgRCY3ie5HzSc_OcVfj-WIZDLone1wH=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPgrUaSUTyLNGqRRwzgzbIk1Q_X6hncvFA6qS1r=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMXDn_QYrdkCEdGgZ4Xht1Mwf1WdDXKPSQyWwj3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><Resp>None</Resp><gmap_id>0x80c1cdd4a9f92733:0x774098d1f48b090< /gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<Date>1599497708084<//Date><Rating>4< /Rating>< Review>
Stayed here for one day and night in Loop C for labor day weekend,  make sure to take a canopy some areas don't have trees so there isn't much shade. It was pretty full but we got lucky enough to find a spot. I enjoyed my stay here the lake had some algae but nothing too crazy. The bathrooms were closed for whatever reason but they did have porta potty. The camp comes with a table and campfire ring. When you arrive grab an envelope and look for a spot, the directions should be on the envelope and afterwards just deposit it into a tube they have there which is right next to the  station.It was $17 for one day/night stay.<//Review>

< Review>
12/11/20 Update: CAMP 9 IS CLOSED BECAUSE OF COVID!  This is the only dump station that has fresh water and garbage.

I didn't go into the campground, I just used the RV dump station, which accepts credit cards.  Be aware, there is potable water, but you have to look for it.  I filled my tank with the water supplied by the dump station, then I found the potable water as I was leaving.  They should have a sign that shows you where the potable water faucet is.  I have a filter on my hose; hopefully I won't get sick from the non-potable water (although, I don't know if it is actually non-potable or if it comes from the same source as the potable water).<//Review>

<Response>None< /Response>< text>
Campsites are on the lake or up the hill with great views. There isn't any shade but most sites can accommodate a motorhome or trailer. There is a dump station and a boat launch ramp. A good campground for lake users. Should note in extreme low water years the lake does not reach the campground. There is a campground host and fees are charged.</text>

<Review>Went in for the first time as I have just recently purchased a used Volvo. I went to Ming's because of the great reviews, the friendliness I experienced on the phone, and my car, with its previous owner, was regularly serviced there for the last 10 years. I went in to replace the headlights with an after market brand and replace a front headlight washer cap. One headlight did not fit properly so I decided to (after both had been installed ) to send both of them back and try a restoration kit instead (which they also do there, but I did on my own and they came out great. 3m Kit). The other piece they could not replace, I needed something more that was thought to be had by the Volvo parts dept., but turned out it was the wrong part and the other was not available. Wayne made sure that I got a safety inspection as I am driving to Alaska. They went above and beyond helping me out, giving me information on what to fix with my car, giving me information on the history ( I had the previous owners permission- privacy  is respected here) and all this they ended up doing for free as nothing technically got done, but they certainly did a lot of work. I wanted to pay for their time. The takeaway- I wish this shop was going to be where I live in Alaska. I trust these guys and felt very well taken care of. Highly recommend!<//Review>< Pictures>

<gmapID>0x80dcd76bd975c089:0xf4195772558d4a20< /gmapID>< Text>
My husband and I had previously used American Vision Windows to install two front windows and an upstairs bedroom window last year.  We were so happy with the experience we decided to get the rest of the windows in the house done as well as the three sliding glass doors.  Since we were going to have all the openings in the house covered, we also decided it would be the time to replace the huge old entry door and sidelights we had with a nice new double door with windows.

We called up Peter, who had sold us the last set of windows, and he came out a few times to walk us through all of our options for the sliders and to make sure the new windows would be the same as the ones we previously had AVW install.  Same as before, Peter was awesome and extremely helpful in working with our budget.

When it came time for measuring, the AVW representative that came to the house was super helpful and even made a special note to our kitchen window as the existing window was going to pose a challenge to retrofit.  We were a little nervous when this was pointed out to us, but he told us that they can handle just about anything and they would make the finished product look right.

Fast forwarding a few months, we got the call for the install and were super happy.  Jason had called us to schedule and then followed up with us two days prior to make sure everything was good to go and if we had any questions.

When install day came, we were told the crew would be at our house between 8:30 am and 9:30 am.  8:00 am on the dot we have the two crews, one for the windows and one for the door, show up and they were ready to go!  They introduced themselves and walked my husband through the order while the rest of the team started setting up.

No joke, the windows and sliders were demoed in about an hour!  They worked super fast and clean, which was nice since it was going to be enough of a challenge putting back the furniture and window treatments later.  Everyone on the window install team was super nice: Jesse, Miguel, Juan, and Steve were very friendly and did a great job.  It was interesting how fast the windows went in and then how much time and care was taken to insulate the gaps, install the molding, and get the windows in show room condition.  The windows and sliders were amazing!  We couldn't believe this was our house!  The window crew was done about 2:30 pm, which was hard to believe that they were able to knock everything out in that amount of time.  The final walkthrough was such a treat, with the challenging kitchen window turning out perfect with a great stucco patch to fix the unsightly gap in the old window.  Total pros!!

The door crew also did an amazing job and wow, that door really made a difference.  Henry and Carlos were great, making the needed adjustments to the opening to get the door in there just right.  Being a double door, we were very sensitive to how the door lined up and how the hardware worked.  When we tried out the door with Henry, everything was nice and snug with the hardware working absolutely perfect.  No more misaligned deadbolt where we had to wiggle the door to get it to set.  No more old heavy wood door!  This was amazing.  Henry was even nice enough to stay behind and quickly re-key the hardware to our existing keys so we could save a trip back to Home Depot to make new keys.  Henry even installed our smart deadbolt and made it look easy.  Everything is working flawlessly!

This was another great experience with American Vision Windows.  We couldn't be happier with everyone we encountered along the way.  The windows, sliders, and entry door have done an amazing job in transforming the look of our house!  We are looking forward to actually being able to open our windows to enjoy the breeze, having sliders that actually slide (imagine that!), and an entry door that is a welcoming focal point to our house.  I can't thank the team enough!!  GREAT JOB!!

- GinGi and Casey Lynch<//Text>

< review>
This review is for RFQ and Window measurement portions. Will update later with actual window installation job.

We were assigned Josh for our window / sliding & french door RFQ. He was able to accommodate our time in the evening to meet with us. He was able to provide succinct answers to our questions. For the most part, nothing was confusing, and if it was, again, we were able to get our answer. After a few weeks we were able to select American Vision out of four other bids to work on our project. Once again, Josh was able to accommodate our busy schedule and meet us in the evening to complete the paperwork. He also came with booties and a mask.

For the measurement portion, Albert came out about a week or so later to get final measurements. He also came with booties and a mask. He answered some questions relating to the outside trim and how it would work installing the frame on the outside. What would be covered up, etc. He finished up the measurement and filled me in on final details. Now we're set for the window installation.

The only bad thing I can say is that the lead-time for the actual windows is way out there since everyone seems to be installing new windows these days (what we heard from American and the other contractors). We'll just have to be patient.

***4/26/21 Update***: Just wanted to give a shout out to American Vision Windows for taking care of us. Windows were installed and look great. We did run into some issues with the roof and window type - but we were very satisfied with how Mike handled the situation. If we have any window projects in the future, we'd definitely give AVW a look again.< /review>

< Review>

In our experience, American Vision Windows gave us a fair price and provided us excellent customer service for our new windows and door.  For the in-home estimate, the windows measurement and the installation appointments, AVW people from Orange location all showed up on time as scheduled. <rate>5</rate><review>I talked with several different companies before settling on one company.  I didn't want to go to all the effort and expense to install mediocre windows that might prematurely fail to perform the way I wanted.  Also, I wanted American made windows installed by actual employees that are trained by the company, not subcontractors.  American Vision Windows easily met all my needs, and their Anlin Del Mar series seemed perfect!

Our salesman, Robert, did a great job helping us select the perfect set of windows for our needs.  Robert was able to generate fast quotes and last-minute changes with sleight of hand, which was super helpful considering my wife's indecisiveness.  Eventually, we pulled the trigger on a last-minute bay window with Queen Anne engraving.  Robert was able to reassure us both throughout an otherwise expensive, confusing process.

Probably one of the more important issues that came up was the city's fire egress requirements.  Turns out that windows must have a minimum size and area that allow for firemen to enter each bedroom in the event of a fire.  My house is old enough that the original windows were no longer up to the current building code.  All the other companies that I met with had missed that requirement and quoted me for windows that would never pass a building inspection!  Upon entering my bedrooms, however, Robert immediately noticed that my windows would have to be enlarged.  Sure, that meant I had to pay more money, but Robert's knowledge and obvious honesty made me want to rely on American Vision Windows for the whole job!

There is a certain amount of time that must pass between signing a contract for new windows and the actual day of installation--the windows are made according to measurements taken on the house.  But I was not left in a lurch during this time!  American Vision Windows periodically sent out emails informing me about the current state of my windows, what to expect next, information about how my windows were being crafted, as well as information about the company from Bill & Kathleen.  Once my new windows were finished being crafted, Andy and Ryan called me up and schedule a day and time for the installation.  Andy was also super helpful and worked closely with me during scheduling my building inspection with the city.

On installation day, three trucks arrived at 8:00AM full of workers ready to get started installing my new windows.  Within minutes, Pascual, Miguel, Carlos, Aaron, Henry, and Brian were working in every room of my house, removing my old windows and installing the new windows.  As I mentioned above, a couple of my windows had to be enlarged to meet the city's building codes.  These guys were great--with machine-like precision, they demoed my old windows, prepared my rough-in window openings, cut into the stucco where necessary, reinforced my house's frame, and installed the new windows and the bay window by, like, 3:00PM.  The enlarged windows and the bay window would require some stucco patch work, but on the inside, everything was painted with primer and ready for fresh paint.  Even without paint, though, everything looked so much better than before!

On stucco patch day, Albert and Joe arrived promptly at 8:00AM and had everything patched and stuccoed by 12:00PM or so!  These guys are super skilled in cement work--they even modded some brickwork near my kitchen windows so they'd match all the other windows.  Albert and Joe happily worked with me and answered all my questions about cement, stucco, primer, and paint.  And, their stucco work looks better than I had imagined, I can't wait to paint it!

I am grateful to all of these guys for their solid skills and great work, and I am super glad I went with American Vision Windows.  Too bad I can't hire them to renovate my back yard, lol.  So, I wholeheartedly recommend American Vision Windows for all you window needs!</review>< pictures>

< text>
I know it sounds corny to think there are actually differences in a vinyl window, especially when you'd think a window is a window is a window, I mean, what's the difference?? They all look the same, smell the same, feel the same...right?
So the only difference would be price...No?

Well, NO!

About 8 years ago when our firstborn was just a little over a year old, we had 2 double windows in our house that needed to be replaced. Previous owners had installed some vinyl windows in most of the rooms except for the master bedroom and the front bedroom. We called American Vision Windows in Orange and asked them to come out and give us a quote. (I‚Äôd heard them on the radio station I was working at so I figured they'd save me some money‚Ä¶maybe even a lot of money).

However, their quote was actually higher than I expected, and definitely higher than some other window advertisers I had heard on the radio, so, I was really thinking about not using them.

But, my wife and I talked about it and in the end we chose to buy from American Vision Windows because we loved their business motto and we did see some differences in the make of the vinyl windows. To be honest, I didn't really care for the sales rep that much, but we absolutely loved what they were about as a company.

I'm so glad we decided to use American Vision!

Today, 8 ¬Ω years later, those windows are still keeping the unwanted noise out, the cool air, and, or heat, in and looking like they're brand new. Amazing!

So many other companies that we considered buying from at the time are no longer in business so who knows what we would have ended up with. Before any one of you decide to sign up with this company, be aware of the issues you will have.

So based on this I decided to sign up with them.

A few hours later I decided to phone Mitchell to verify that indeed what I was told was a fact.  To my surprise I found out that Mitchell has no agreement with Auto Vitals to integrate with them, and that‚Äôs the email I got from Mitchell (as per our conversation), Mitchell 1 Manager SE does not integrate with Auto Vitals. So as a result after the conversation I had with Mitchell four hours later, I sent an email to Auto Vitals to cancel my contract.

If you want to do business with a company like this, here is an example what you would get, and I wish you good luck. By the way, the only way to have 100% integration with Mitchell management software is with Bolt On Technology, Check them out!

This really sucks, I feel a little mislead.

<user_id>105597181213729689289</user_id>< user_name>
craig zale< /user_name>
< time>
1476977703811<//time>
<rating>5</rating>< Review>
One of the best tools to run today's professional repair and service shops. We started our auto repair shop in 1996 and up until two years ago we still used paper handwritten  job tickets for the techs to  write up their findings and the the recommended repairs and parts needed. This then had to be hand carried back to the front desk and then typed into the computer by a service advisor . After the service advisor figured out what the tech was trying to say (reading handwriting) he or she then could start the estimating process. When questions came up the service advisor would than have to keep going to the tech to get clarification on vehicle types for things like a rotor size or lug stud size for brake rotors , or go see the problem in person so they can describe it to the customer. Then the customer had only the service advisors word and hopped they could explain what the tech was trying to say well enough for the customer to make an informed decision.
This is quite literally a "best thing since sliced bread thing" Just the time savings  is well worth the program, than adding in pictures and a way to highlight them for the customer to see  it  from their smartphone or pc and also  the tech being able to instantly pull up history and also have a digital inspection sheet with voice or hand typed notes and check box recommendations. I could go on for another hour but just give this a try/ do a demo and really look hard at it. If you are serious about your shop's future success then this is a real game changer.</Review>

<user_id>103747766318464642484</user_id><Name>Kristin Sedgwick<//Name><gmap_id>0x80c2a4cfdd9c475f:0xa23e8d365323987< /gmap_id><Rate>5< /Rate>< time>
1613259269752<//time>
< Text>
The food was delicious. Mussels (in a can) from Spain with sour dough crustini were delicious. The dipping sauces offered awesome extra punch of taste, esp the home made mustard. The prime rib sandwiches on hawaiian rolls, though small because they are sliders, we're delectable. The meat was perfectly medium rare and plentiful. But the best part was the drinks. We had the yellow jacket  - mescal, honey, spice - and a Paloma. Delicious and apparently part of an all day happy hour. Grateful for the folks sitting next to us who told us about it. The wait staff was attentive, always available, but a not as forthcoming with the happy hour options. We figured it out, and it was worth it. $5 drinks. I'll definitely go back, esp when indoor dining is back. The inside space is gorgeous.<//Text>

<Rate>5</Rate>< review>
My friend and I had reservations at another restaurant but we saw Misfit and changed our mind and dined here. We opt to sit on the patio. It was a beautiful warm day and it was perfect.
The interior is a darker ambiance with a wall filled with alcohol.

Can't remember our servers name but he was very nice and pleasant.  He recommended a drink for my friend and she enjoyed it.

We had the shrimp ceviche and that was so refreshing.

Overall, I loved this restaurant.  Next time I'm in Santa Monica Imma definitely dine here again. Wanted to give a shout out to Nicholas! Thanks for the fun and laughter.</review>

<rate>5</rate><Text>Five stars basically for everything!

My uncle came to visit from Australia so my sister and I decided to take him out here with my parents on a Saturday night and it was the perfect spot.

We got seated upstairs where it was nice and cozy, less noise than downstairs, perfect dim lighting and an excellent waitress, wish I can remember her name. < user_name>
Shanelle S<//user_name>
< Date>
1564709889206<//Date>
<rate>4</rate>< Review>
Do you like $5 lunches? I do - which is why I take friends who are visiting during a weekday to the Misfit for the $5 Bar Fly deals. Monday-Friday the Misfit will have one dish for $5 if you sit at the bar between 12-4 (no saving seats). Happy hour also happens during the same time. My favorite is the fried chicken sandwich on Thursday‚Äôs. The chicken is moist on the inside but perfectly crunch on the outside and complemented by the coleslaw accompaniment.  On this visit, we tried the ahi tuna burger which was cooked rare and was so very good. I liked the brioche bun and there was a slight level of spiciness that went well with the pickle provided. They give you complimentary salt chocolate chip cookies at the end when you pay your check.

Love the food, the service is hit or miss. I think the bartenders get stressed when there are a lot of people and so you need to be patient. However the server who recently helped us thanked us for our patience and was nice overall. It might be a struggle to find a spot at the bar so just go during an off time to avoid crowds. The decor is cool and hip although it‚Äôs a bit annoying that the bathrooms are on the second floor. There‚Äôs indoor and outdoor seating.

Overall, given its proximity to Third St Promenade, this restaurant has really good food. Try to come during lunch or happy hour to take advantage of the deals, otherwise just enjoy the free chocolate chip cookies and know that you‚Äôre eating at a high quality restaurant.</Review>

< text>
Came here with a couple of girlfriends on a Saturday night and it was vibin'.  We were able to grab drinks at the bar while we waited for our seats.  The servers were pretty attentive and food and drinks came out pretty quick.  As you walk in, your eyes are naturally drawn to the high ceilings and cool looking bar.  With a library style floor to ceiling shelving of liquor bottles and books at the top, the concept is pretty impressive and quite memorable.  It's quite dark and it gets super noisy - perfect if you're with a big group or a girl's night.

We ordered a couple of dishes to share and the Mac n Cheese was pretty good.  However, the sangria was less to be desired - super watery and the fruits they used seemed cheap or rather they ran out and they tried to scavenge what they could.</text>

1580940446202< /Date>
<Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
1940s feel to this beautiful bar and restaurant. The food can be pricey but if you take advantage of the daily burger special (Wednesday is ahi Tuna) and the happy hour (every day until 7pm) it's very reasonable. Be sure to put your name on the list for a seat at the bar. Kevin the bartender will take great care of you and takes pride in his Mixology. I had the Mac n Cheese with chorizo. Despite its small appearance it the spot. The drink I had was good but not great. Kevin, without me even mentioning it, made me a new drink with the help of another bar tender and it was superb. They have a small outdoor seating area and a large indoor restaurant. It was bustling for a Wednesday afternoon. Highly recommend in Santa Monica!< /Review>

< review>
One of my favourite bars in Santa Monica. The decor and style is very pretty and cosy. The main bar is made of an old wooden book shelf and looks like a library but contains liquors instead of books. The barkeepers are very friendly and dressed up in white button downs and ties. They have good cocktails and decent food.
They have a happy hour from 12-7 pm with assorted cocktails for $7. The interior is darkish/red with lots of wood so good for a date. However, it u usually very crowded and also loud due to the amount of people. Plus is the outdoor seating.<//review>

< review>
Great classy escape from the storm of tourists on Third Street Promenade, and surprise, it has the best daily happy hour in Santa Monica (12-7pm $7.50 for cocktails, and many other drinks). There's a catch though, it's very difficult to get a seat at pique hours, and forget about it if you don't like waiting on a Friday or Saturday. Very good cocktails‚Äîthe Clocktower Manhattan recently left the menu, but it was one of the best Manhattans in LA. The gastropub style food menu is quite good as well. It's a great spot to stop with a notebook and do some writing, or for a quiet conversation. The atmosphere is sophisticated, and despite the heavy amount of tourists and obnoxious characters trying to impress dates, there's usually a good mix of locals too. Misfit feels like a slice of New York or Chicago¬†that somehow found it's way to the beachfront of the Pacific.</review>

Came out to The Misfit for a girls night/birthday outing. Loved the atmosphere - warm, low lighting with dark wood and large stuffed chairs. The food was tasty and the service was great. I thought the food was a little more adventurous than I normally like but I still found a few things that I liked.

The pricing was spot on with the other reviews - mid range/$$. Also, go early or try for a reservation.  We went out on a Wednesday evening at 6:00 PM and there were plenty of people there when we arrived and some standing outside for table when we left. The bar had people lined up all evening.< /text>

<UserId.>116105288386186256756< /UserId.>< text>
Best thing is undoubtedly the free sea salt chocolate chip cookies at the end and I love the atmosphere and decor. Everything else needs work. I went with a party of 8 at lunchtime and all of our main courses came out at different times - no one asked us if we'd prefer them staggered and it was awkward as some people had hot dishes and didn't feel comfortable eating them. For shared appetizers, we had to request a utensil each time - this place is busy at lunch, always, and I feel like not quite set up to accomodate it.

Food wise, I tried a few things. Veggie burger was great. Brussel sprouts were not bad. Beet hummus looked and tasted like mustard, not at all like hummus, and came with a weird medley of pickled vegetables. Lentil soup and kale salad were both bland and the soup came out lukewarm.</text>

< Date>
1569772397267<//Date>
< rating>
5<//rating>
<text>Oh. so so so so so good!
It was walking distance from the hotel so when I saw the fabulous rating with over 3000 reviews I knew we needed to go. Went for dinner last night. Our waiter was adorable and VERY good about helping us make selections, and then making us feel good about everything we choose.
They have a great selection of local beers, I can't remember what the one I choose was called - I remember it had the name 'magical and delicious' in it and that's pretty much why I ordered it!
We got the baba ganoush, crab & corn fritters, the mac & cheese, shrimp diablo, chicken sausage skewer, and the short rib skewers.
Oh. Em. Gee. EVERYTHING was simply marvelous. Cooked to perfection, sauces all delicious and paired perfectly with each dish. I don't know that I had a favorite - the short rib was my favorite of the skewers and the shrimp diablo was my least favorite of the small plates (but not by much, so don't overlook it based on that).
At the end of the meal you get a chocolate sea salt cookie that is SO good you want to grab the bowl and make a run for it out the door (but don't, that's just rude - instead ask your waiter to purchase some to take home with you)
The decor is so fun - it's in the 1929 clock tower building and the decor totally gives you that vibe. The bar is the focal point and there is SO much to see in it. I almost wish they weren't as busy as they were so that I could have gone up and checked it out closer - but busy is good so I'd never wish a business NOT have clients. :)

If I am in the area again this is DEFINITELY going to be a repeat visit!!</text><pictures>None< /pictures><response>None< /response><gmap_id>0x80c2a4cfdd9c475f:0xa23e8d365323987< /gmap_id></record>

<Text>This is one of my favorite spots for dinner and drinks when I'm around 3rd street Santa Monica area. It has a unique atmosphere that is great for casual hangout with friends or a dinner date.

Favorite Foods & Drinks:
-Shrimp Ceviche (Baja style)

-Hand Cut Kennebec Fries (Huge serving bowl full of shoestring fries, easily feeds 4 people)

-The Misfit Burger (Classic & simple with cheddar, mayo, and house pickles)

-Crispy Chicken Sandwich (Jidori chicken, fennel slaw, and spicy mayo) *Favorite Dish*

-Pitcher of White Sangria (Easily serves 4 people)

-At the end of the meal they give you a free salted chocolate chip cookie!

And if you go during weekday lunch they have a "Bar Fly Lunch" menu if you sit at the bar. $5 lunch special of the day that changes every day.

With $5 offerings like their Saigon Crispy Chicken, The Misfit Burger, The Ahi Burger, etc you really can't go wrong!<//Text><rate>5</rate>< username>

< rate>
5< /rate>
< review>
My girlfriend and I visited LA for the weekend and this place was highly sought after on google reviews and with the locals. They were right. The bartenders are over the top mix masters. My girlfriend told the bartender what she liked and he created a drink for her palate. The food is just ridiculously amazing. Broccoli is delicious with just enough spice. Cauliflower curry is a must for curry lovers. The tuna is super fresh. They use a really high quality grass fed ground beef (best beef I've ever had) for all their burgers... Definitely recommend trying the Green chile burger.

We went here our first evening in LA and were so impressed we came back the next night. The second night we had a dish that we didn't like. Not only did the server remove it from our tab and replace the dish, the manager personally came over to apologize and handed us a $50 voucher for our next visit. Next time we're in LA we will definitely come back here. This is what all restaurants should strive to become.</review>

< Text>
The food at Mistfit changes periodically and never disappoints. Love the salads and the lobster roll sliders. Brunch is excellent and there is an extended happy hour. Great craft cocktails-- they make several with grapefruit that are the best on the patio on a nice day. Also love the complimentary chocolate chip cookies with sea salt at the end of the meal. I have purchased additional packages of them for visiting guests. Only downside is that it can be very difficult to hear and have a conversation inside and at the bar on the evenings it's very crowded--no place to stand and people constantly elbowing and pushing you. Patio is great though.</Text>

<review>Absolutely my favorite date night spot - amazing speakeasy ambiance and upscale but still affordable food.  The waitstaff is great and very friendly and the mood is always light.  Their menu is structured similarly to tapas, but the serving sizes are about double that for their entrees.  Everything is fresh and delicious, and they cycle dishes through the menu frequently.

Their mixed drinks are fantastic, and we love to get their sangria pitcher - it's only $20 and a great deal for a night out.  They finish each meal with free, warm, salted chocolate chip cookies which are the best part!  The only negative is that the tables are pretty close together so the whole restaurant gets pretty loud, but overall it's a great choice.< /review>< GmapID>

<rating>1</rating>< Text>
My friends and I were looking for a nice place in Santa Monica for good cocktails and a nice ambiance. Online reviews told us the Misfit was the place;  and it looked it until we actually wanted to order.

As a person who has visited many establishments in many locations, I've seen a lot. I have never had a team of bartenders be so rude, pretentious, and make customers (other people at the bar included) wait so long for a drink, a check, or otherwise.

When it came time to close out the check, I had to wait 25 minutes for my card. The bartenders were unapologetic and weren't shy in showing a disdainful attitude.

Safe to say that none of my friends (or the other people at the bar, for that matter, I assume) will return to the Misfit. Well-deserved name.< /Text>

<UserId.>110022871276795678079<//UserId.><username>Sydney Snyder</username><time>1524586136972< /time><Rating>5< /Rating>< Text>
This is one of my top three favorite restaurants in LA. The servers, hosts, and bartenders here are almost always the friendliest, most welcoming people. I literally dream about their french fries. Super skinny, perfectly seasoned with honey mustard dipping sauce. I feel tears forming in my eyes just thinking about them. Their mac and cheese is super yummy. I've also enjoyed some of their soups, their spicy fried chicken, and tons of other dishes. Almost everything on their menu is gluten free. Their cocktails are also delicious. Don't be intimidated if you see a line forming outside. They have a very efficient waitlist and will get ahold of you when you're up. But they're usually pretty quick. The bar is PACKED during happy hour, so we almost always just get a table and eat, too. Beautiful environment, as well. Mmmmmmmmm!<//Text>

<rate>3<//rate><text>Just found this place to be good and not great. The fried chicken is good but the drinks here are much better. Koo place to jave a bite and a beer!
This place is beautiful inside. Fell in love with the theme and the style/decor.
Customer service was great, no complaints what so ever.

Dinner:
I had the the AHI BURGER sushi grade tuna, hand ground and seared rare, avocado, spicy mayo on a bun. Which wasn't all that great. It was bland I didn't taste the spicy mayo and the avocado tasted over ripe, It had that crappy taste had to remove it from the burger.
My friend had the CRISPY CHICKEN SANDWICH with jidori chicken breast, fennel-apple slaw, spicy mayo. Now that was tasteful from the bite she let me have.
For me the best part was the side of fries that we ordered.
I can see how this is one of their popular dishes.

<time>1413953373590</time>< Rate>

<review>This is a 5-star happy hour place, but a 3 star restaurant when happy hour is not in effect so I gave it a solid four. $5 dollars for all of their signature cocktails sounds like a great deal to get buzzed at the Santa Monica pier. I would recommend most of the drinks except the Pimm's punch unless you want to have what seemed like a thimble size amount of alcohol. The food was ok, I got the 3 sliders combo and the slider were relatively small and overpriced. The prime rib slider was delicious though and their chocolate chip cookies aren't too bad. <user_id>115714525439845252049< /user_id><username>Carlin Yuen<//username><date>1364395741889</date><Rate>4<//Rate><review>Came here for dinner on a business trip. Really cool decor -- like an old school library mashed up with a classy bar with really high ceilings, but it totally works -- well designed and interesting. The lighting is dim but not straining, and it gets kinda loud in there.

It was pretty busy when we came in, and service was a little sparse but they were still pretty fast and friendly about it. Drinks are about $9 a pop for a well drink, and the food is all kinda tapas-like with some larger dishes as well.

Tried the prime rib French dip nik nik sliders, the bacon-wrapped dates, and the fried chicken sandwich. The dates were decent, although I think the bacon doesn't balance with the date as well as I thought it would. The french dip sliders were great: a little pricey for the amount you get, but the meat was soft and still tasty, and the dip worked pretty well.

My favorite by far was the fried chicken sandwich though. Big portion, plus a delicious mix of texture and flavor. There's a nice spicy kick to it, and the crispy crunch to the chicken worked really well with the marinade / sauces on it. Would definitely go back for that sandwich again!</review>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

<user>102191991550028128685< /user>< Name>
Hanae K</Name>
<Time>1451299566202< /Time>< rating>
4<//rating>
< Review>
They had the best presentation I've seen for an Irish Whiskey. It was served in a wine glass with a side of french press! This is probably my favorite bar near 3rd st promenade, especially because they spoil you with their famous complimentary sea salt cookies :)

A bit crowded at the narrow lightly-dimmed bar on a Sunday night. We got lucky and found a good spot to sit. I ordered white sangria which was refreshing, nothing crazy amazing.

I liked their 1920-ish ambience a lot and the service was great.

::FOOD::
we ordered random stuff, all of them were pretty sweet...I couldn't taste the sweetness from my sangria because of that.
- bacon wrapped dates with goat cheese, nuts and topped with parmesan: delicious and rich, share it with people
- $3 pistachio gelato: not sure what the hype is all about, still yummy and rich
- complimentary sea salt cookie: the reason why people love them = BUTTER</Review>

<Text>I came here for dinner yesterday with a friend around 8:30PM. We forgot to make reservations so we had to wait about 30 mins for a table. We got seated at the smallest possible table upstairs, in a corner overlooking the restaurant. I already knew our table was going to be too small for us but it was getting late and we didn't want to wait any longer to eat.

What We Ordered:
- Bacon Wrapped Dates
- Housemade Shoestring French Fries
- Baked Mac and Cheese with Chorizo
- Prime Rib French Dip Nik Niks****
- Green Chili Burger
- Sea Salt Chocolate Chip Cookies**** - FREE but we bought some to take home too!

We ordered the recommended items her co workers suggested. The Bacon Wrapped Dates were a little too sweet for me but my friend enjoyed them. The Shoestring Fries were too soggy. I wished they were crispier. The Honey Mustard sauce was the savior for them though! It was soooo good! The Baked Mac and Cheese with Chorizo could have been cheesier but I love cheese. My friend thought they were cheesy enough. They didn't skimp on the chorizo either! It was 50% mac and 50% chorizo!! The Green Chili Burger was a little too charred for our likely. It tasted a little burnt. It definitely fell short in flavor. I do not know if it was because it came AFTER the Prime Rib French Dip Nik Niks or it really just isn't that good.

The highlight of the night.... the PRIME RIB FRENCH DIP NIK NIKS!!! OMG! It was sooo tender and melted in your mouth! The dipping sauce was what really made the dish though. It complimented the meat perfectly! I will go back JUST for this and the SEA SALT CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES of course. :) We bought some to take home and they were fresh out of the oven warm...mmm...sooo good. I can't wait to eat them today!

Only complaint for the night was the fact it took us forever to flag down our waitress to pay for our meal. It was busy but she was no where in sight and I really wanted some napkins after eating those delicious, buttery cookies.

TIPS: MAKE RESERVATIONS! We left the restaurant at 10PM and there was STILL a line outside. It was a Thursday night...can't imagine how it is on the weekends lol.<//Text><Pics>None<//Pics><Response>None<//Response>< gmap_id>

<Review>Freaking amazeballs!!

How does one go wrong with a 7 day a week HH??? That's right ladies and gents you can quaff down some delicious libations for half its price! I was lucky enough to order the ever-so-yummy white sangria and was more surprisingly appeased ^_^. At $7 a pop I had two for the price of one ($3.50 each for those of you who hate math).

**I believe HH ends at 7 but don't quote me because we were in at 3ish and out before 6ish**

Now not only do they have tasty drinks but they have equally scrumptious cuisine options.

I got the crispy lobster nik niks , "savannah style", pancetta, heirloom tomato, Russian dipping sauce. The "nik niks" are essentially sliders (comes with 2) that are deceptively filling. The lobster was perfectly fried and the entire dish was absurdly perfect. I opted out of the pancetta but I am sure its salty flavor would have complimented the dish well.

I also had the ahi burger, sushi grade tuna, carefully ground and seared rare, avocado, spicy mayo on a butter bun. YUMMMM I can't for the life of me distinguish which I preferred more because they were both amazing. Great flavor combo and the bun was amazing.

BOTH great options.

The fries are also tasty and you get a huge sharable mountain for only $3.50

My friend ordered the baked mac + cheese, green chile, brown rice pasta with chorizo and it was the most mind blowing cheese fest ever. Once I am off my diet I will launch my face into a big steaming pile of this dish because the aroma and visuals were just tooo tempting!

Overall GREAT place to good for food or drinks. Great prices and great flavors.

**Also service was MARVELOUS. I told my waitress that I would need a drink in about 7 mins and magically one appeared once I finished my first in perfect timing. She was incredibly nice and prompt! **<//Review>< Pics>

< Name>
Monita H< /Name>
<rating>5<//rating><Date>1439836233386</Date><user_id>103568399835730799941</user_id><resp>None< /resp>< Review>
I've been here a few times and it's one of the few places that I enjoying going back to in LA county. :)

Their cocktails are phenomenal and the wine selection is pretty decent. :) I love their happy hour, the food is good and not ridiculously expensive, and the service has always been very consistent.

The interior is well done. It's got a dim, party environment. It has a nice contrast with the overall kind of rough and dark atmosphere with hints of curves and old school design details to soften the interior up. A huge fan of the antique-like mirrors and the tin ceiling tiles.

The noise can be a little crazy with all the people and the music. It's definitely very happening during the evenings.

Love the Head In the Clouds, KD Bees Knees, and the Peach Orchard Boar. :)

Kale + quinoa salad w/ salmon. Gets a solid Five Stars. The grapes and the Manchego cheese gives the kale a much needed flavor boost. Salmon is a great addition to the dish! It doesn't come out dry and that is really key. :)

Recently tried their new menu addition: the Open Faced Grilled Cheese. Very excellent. It's got a sweet kick to it. Not really what I expected when I took the first bite. But I love surprises! And this was definitely a pleasant surprise! :D

One dish that was fairly Meh was the Ahi Burger. It didn't really stand out to me and the Ahi didn't really have a dominating presence. It didn't have as much potential as the other dishes I've tried here. I had a mound of avocado but the ahi was really lacking. Not bad, but not great either.

Their complimentary Sea Salt Cookies are where it's at! Highly addictive! Super delicious! Is a nice gesture at the end of a meal.

Service has always been friendly and fast. The waiters constantly checks in to make sure everything is to your satisfaction. The drink runners are quick. The staff made my experience comfortable and I felt well taken care of. :D

Definitely enjoy dropping in here once in awhile!< /Review>

<Text>Summary: Great food, attentive service, slightly pricey but not unreasonably,  cool atmosphere, good drink selection, happy hour, and fun times.  Nothing that we didn't like.  Parking on the street or at a nearby parking structure.  Bathroom's are single occupancy, so be prepared to wait in line to...you know...

My in-laws were in town for Thanksgiving and decided to meet me after work in Santa Monica.  We toured around and enjoyed the sunset, then it was time to find a place to dine.  We made our way to The Misfit after Yelp guided us there (based on overall score and # of reviews).  It was a Wednesday evening at around 5pm, so happy hour was going strong but we were immediately seated in a booth upon walking in.

The decor inside is dark, and somewhat loud due to the bar-atmosphere, but well executed in an old-timey, book-room sort of way.  Dark woods, stacks of books behind the bar, and vintage looking pieces along the walls.  Despite the old style atmosphere, when we first met our server we observed that she was taking our order on a smartphone or PDA-sized tablet at the table.  Technology at its finest.

We ordered some drinks to start since it was happy hour and mixed drinks were half price.  My wife ordered a Bijou, which tasted like a sparkling greyhound, I ordered the white Sangria (delicious), my Father-in-law had a Manhattan, and my Mother-in-law had some other fruity mixed drink that she, too, enjoyed.

We soon ordered.  Here are the various things we got:

Gumbo - Thick, spicy, hot, tasty.  Not a traditional-style creation, but a delicious one, nonetheless.  Pretty filling too.

Mac 'n Cheese - Slightly on the oily side, but piping hot, cheesy, delicious, excellently textured pasta, etc. Awesome.

Kale and Quinoa salad - Fresh, substantial, decoratively presented, and tasty (from what I heard).  Mom-in-law seemed to enjoy this.

Chickpea Wraps - Spicy and tasty.  Filling, and healthy.

Lobster Nik Niks - Nicely fried, excellent texture, a decent amount of lobster, though certainly more slider-sized than full sandwich sized.  Quite good though.

Green Chile Burger - A nice kick, but missing produce on top.  Tasty, and pretty well prepared though.

Brussels Sprouts - Nice and firm, tasty, and in large portion.  Quite good.

BBQ Salmon with Arugula Salad - Also filling, healthy, fresh and delicious.

Ultimately, the common element in all of the food was freshness and quality.  Those two elements entailed deliciousness that we all enjoyed.  While not the cheapest meal around, it was still quite good and worth it.< /Text>< pictures>
None<//pictures>
